body:
With Eclipse Installer 1.30.0 Build 172 you can not Install a 2023-12 version an get the new Instance up with the "Launch automatically".

If you did the same but install a 2023-09 the new Instance comes up automatically.

I found the following workaround.

```
  public Process execute(List<String> command, boolean terminal) throws Exception
  {
    ProcessBuilder processBuilder = new ProcessBuilder(command);
    try
    {
      Map<String, String> environment = processBuilder.environment();
      environment.remove("SWT_GTK3"); //$NON-NLS-1$
    }
    catch (UnsupportedOperationException ex)
    {
      // Ignore.
    }

    Process process = processBuilder.start();
    process.getInputStream().close();
    process.getOutputStream().close();
    process.getErrorStream().close();
    return process;
  }
```
If you insert `    TimeUnit.SECONDS.sleep(1);`
after `    Process process = processBuilder.start();`but before `process.getErrorStream().close();`
you can start a 2023-12 installation

They are generated during the build yes, and **not** checked in. But m2e is able to import them despite the files not being there (I think they must do something to temporarily create them).

![image](https://github.com/eclipse-oomph/oomph/assets/136501322/6044d857-1ab3-4b3e-bde5-721ed81d319a)

I've debugged this and during the Maven import task we do get these projects (because m2e knows about it), but then the MavenProjectFactory only knows to look for pom.xml so the other ones are filtered.

`org.eclipse.oomph.resources.impl.XMLProjectFactoryImpl.doCreateProject(BackendContainer, BackendContainer, IProgressMonitor)`

```java
  @Override
  public final IProject doCreateProject(BackendContainer rootContainer, BackendContainer backendContainer, IProgressMonitor monitor)
  {
    IPath xmlFilePath = new Path(getXMLFileName());
    BackendFile xmlFile = null;

    try
    {
      xmlFile = backendContainer.getFile(xmlFilePath);

      byte[] bytes = xmlFile.getContentBytes(monitor);
      if (bytes.length > 0)
      {
        ByteArrayInputStream bais = new ByteArrayInputStream(bytes);
        DocumentBuilder documentBuilder = XMLUtil.createDocumentBuilder();
        Element rootElement = XMLUtil.loadRootElement(documentBuilder, bais);

        Description description = new Description(backendContainer);
        fillDescription(description, rootElement);

        return new ExternalProject(backendContainer, description);
      }
    }
    catch (FileNotFoundException ex)
    {
      //$FALL-THROUGH$
    }
    catch (Exception ex)
    {
      String message = NLS.bind(Messages.XMLProjectFactoryImpl_ProblemParsing_exception, xmlFile != null ? xmlFile : xmlFilePath);
      ResourcesPlugin.INSTANCE.log(new Exception(message, ex));
    }

    return null;
  }
```

The XMLProjectFactory tries to find a file in the project for import. For Maven projects, `getXMLFileName()` returns `pom.xml`, and so `null` is returned since that file doesn't exist.

So my potential solutions would be:
1. Modify `XMLProjectFactory` to allow multiple filenames to search if one isn't found. Something like
```java
IPath xmlFilePath = null;
for (var filename : getXMLFileNames()) {
    xmlFilePath = new Path(filename);
    if (xmlFilePath.toFile().exists()) {
        break;
    }
}
...
```
2. Create a project factory for Tycho that knows about these files, similar to above but without modifying the original XMLProjectFactory. You could maybe get m2e to help the factory figure out what the appropriate file is (because there can be many e.g., `.polyglot.META-INF`, `.polyglot.feature.xml`, etc).


My first solution is probably better because they still are xml files, so we can benefit from the xml resource loading that the factory already does. We just have to teach it about different file names besides `pom.xml`.

